The national security advisors of the United States, Japan, and the Republic of Korea (ROK) met to discuss the United States' review of its North Korea policy and other shared concerns. They expressed their commitment to address North Korea's nuclear and ballistic missile programs through trilateral cooperation. The advisors also emphasized the importance of implementing UN Security Council resolutions, preventing proliferation, and maintaining peace and stability on the Korean Peninsula. They discussed reuniting separated Korean families and resolving the abductions issue. The United States reaffirmed its alliance commitments to both Japan and the ROK, while Japan and the ROK highlighted the significance of their bilateral ties and trilateral cooperation. The advisors also discussed collaborating on challenges such as COVID-19, preventing future pandemics, combating climate change, and promoting democracy in Myanmar. They agreed to strengthen their ties and promote a common vision based on shared democratic values.